Gathering commercial oysters is done chiefly by dredging or tonging.However, in certain areas much harvesting was done by oystermen who gather themby hand at low tide. (Image credit: Archival photograph by Mr. Sean Linehan)

A mountain of oysters.  Where spawning conditions are good, oysters in their natural state will attach themselves, one generation atop another, until great ridges of them exist up to high tide.  However, such oysters are poor quality and of little commercial value.  By spreading them out and giving them room togrow, the quality can be improved.  F&W; A-6151. (Image credit: Archival photograph by Mr. Sean Linehan)

Oyster shells are recycled by planting them on soft muddy bottom.  This gives afirm surface for the attachment of young oysters and helps provide larger crops. (Image credit: Archival photograph by Mr. Sean Linehan)

Hundred of starfish dredged or scraped off an oyster bed.  Starfish attack young oysters and threaten the well-being of the oyster crop.  F&WL; 12,416. (Image credit: Archival photograph by Mr. Sean Linehan)

Starfish attacking young oysters.  Special equipment is used to dredge or scrape starfish off oyster beds in order to reduce the damage to the oysters.F&W; 12,001. (Image credit: Archival photograph by Mr. Sean Linehan)
Mackerel being unloaded, salted, and barreled at the Boston Fish Pier.F&WL; 12,351. (Image credit: Archival photograph by Mr. Sean Linehan)

Fisherman casting his net.  Photo F&WL; 12,571. (Image credit: Archival photograph by Mr. Sean Linehan)

Purse seining.  Salmon swimming near the surface are surrounded with a wall ofnetting, which is supported by floats.  Lines are then drawn tight in the lowersurface of the net to purse it into a baglike shape.  The fish are then bailedout of the net.  F&WL; C-1163. (Image credit: Archival photograph by Mr. Sean Linehan)
Shrimp trawl operations.  The 60-foot trawl has been raised preparatory tobrailing out the shrimp.  Photo B-50229. (Image credit: Archival photograph by Mr. Sean Linehan)
Hauling in beach seine  from the Columbia River by horse teams.  F&WL; 12,496. (Image credit: Archival photograph by Mr. Sean Linehan)
Men hauling in beach seine heavy with Columbia River salmon.  F&WL; 12,495. (Image credit: Archival photograph by Mr. Sean Linehan)

This barge-load of salmon attests to why the Alaska salmon fishery was the mostvaluable fishery prosecuted by U. S. fishermen at the time of this photo.F&WL; C-1193. (Image credit: Archival photograph by Mr. Sean Linehan)
Knee-deep in salmon.  Salmon being transferred to a large boat on which they are iced and hauled to a cannery.  F&W; 12,935. (Image credit: Archival photograph by Mr. Sean Linehan)
Brailing salmon from a floating trap.  F&WL; C-1195. (Image credit: Archival photograph by Mr. Sean Linehan)

Salmon being counted when passing through weirs.  By law, a certain percentageof salmon runs had to be allowed to escape commercial fisheries in order tospawn.  To check the percentage, counting weirs were maintained on manystreams.   F&W; - 10,111. (Image credit: Archival photograph by Mr. Sean Linehan)

Beginning of the Alaska King Crab fishery.  Meat from one crab is sufficient tofill several cans.  Scientists of the Fish and Wildlife Service, a forerunner of today's NMFS, showed where to catch crabs and helped develop satisfactorycanning methods. Purse seine operation from 1940.  Much manpower was needed to pull the net after the school of fish was surrounded. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 5 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

Purse seine nets are now larger and can be hauled by power blocks installed inaluminum purse seine boats.  Fewer crewmen are needed to compactthe school, after which the fish are pumped aboard the carrier vessel. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 6 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

Peruvian fishmeal in a warehouse in Port Hueneme, California.  In 1970, theUnited States was the largest importer of fish products in the world. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 10 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Breading shrimp in a Southeast Atlantic plant.  The processing industry hasdeveloped many new convenience products, like breaded shrimp andfish sticks . (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 14 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Chart showing difference between saturated fat molecule  below, and above is apolyunsaturated fat molecule.  The two main features that distinguish fish oilfrom other animal fats are the unusually long fatty acid chains in fish oil andtheir high degree of unsaturation. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 42 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

A BCF home economist is testing a new industry-developed batter for preparingfried fish. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 44 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

A taste panel records its reactions to a new fishery product.  These trainedobservers rate the elements that determine whether the product is of highquality and will appeal to consumers. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 45 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

New appetizing fishery products have become available in recent years.  At theBCF Gloucester Technological Laboratory, shrimp from Maine are preparedwith sauce and attractively packaged. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 54 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Breaded, cooked fish sticks are being packaged before freezing.  the consumeronly has to warm the sticks in an oven.  Frozen fishery products are nowsold in a dazzling variety of forms, and are second to canned products in the U.S. edible fishery supply. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 56 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Laboratory research in fishery food science leads to better handling, processing, marketing, and home preparation of fishery products - as well as changes inproducts to meet changing consumer preferences. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 58 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

An engineer at the Gloucester Technological Laboratory tests newly developedplastic container for shipping iced fresh fish long distances.  Elaborate testsare required to determine the merits of an innovation before it is released toindustry. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 64 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

A technician is packaging fish fillets in a plastic container for demonstrationshipping tests.  Ice will be added before the container is sealed. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 66 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Fishery food scientists carry out research to find the best means of retainingcolor, as well as taste, during storage of frozen fish. Sample at right treatedwith corn syrup solids; sample in center (retaining color) treated with EMQ (ethoxyquinoline), sample on left frozen and lost color. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 68 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Capturing a sperm whale, third quarter, 19th century.  The early origin of thereduction industry that produces fish meal and oil lies in the extinct U.S.whaling industry that reached its peak during the 19th Century. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 70 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

A little-known aspect of the U.S. fisheries is the reduction industry thatproduces fish meal and oil.  Most of the fishmeal goes into feed for good andrapid growth of poultry - chicken broilers, chicken breeders and layers, andturkeys.  Fishmeal is an excellent balanced source of amino acids (components of protein) and adds minerals and vitamins to the feed. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 72 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

Scales shed from herring are collected to make pearl essence - a lustrous anddecorative finish applied to many products like baby toys, dolls, clothing,jewelry, etc.  Small herring, caught along the Maine coast, furnish theprincipal raw material for our pearl essence industry.  The fish will be cannedand sold as Maine sardines. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 79 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Unloading kelp, a seaweed, from harvesting vessel, Port Hueneme, Calif.  Thisaquatic plant will be processed into meal and used as a component in feed forlivestock and poultry.  The meal adds minerals and vitamins (chiefly riboflavin) to the feed. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 80 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Studying mating habits of a pair of tanner crabs.  To calculate the sustainableharvest that can be expected, biologists must have a thorough understandingof the life history of a species and how it reacts to changes in theenvironment. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 88 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

On board a BCF research vessel, fishery biologists are measuring fish and taking blood samples for stock analysis.  Each species of fish or shellfish iscomposed of stocks or subpopulations, which may differ slightly in structure,physiology, or rate of growth. Information on stocks enables biologists todetermine the sustainable yield of each stock. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 91 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

The croaker is the dominant fish caught with trawls in the northern Gulf ofMexico.  Large croakers find a ready market as food fish.  In the 1950's a newfishery was started to supply small-sized bottomfishes - mainly croaker, spot,sand trout, and silver trout - to canneries packing pet food. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 207 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Famed cannery row has gone out of business as a center of sardine canning.  Inthe 1930's and 1940's, the California sardine industry was the largest in theUnited States, landing a peak of 1.5 billion pounds in 1936.  The sardinepopulation had dwindled to almost nothing by the late 1960's but had beenreplaced by an even larger anchovy population. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 218 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Cleaning albacore loins in preparation for canning this premium whitemeat tuna.The discarded dark parts of the loin go into canned pet food.  Tunas andtuna-like fishes  -- with average catch of about 285 million pounds during 1963-1967 -- dominated the California fisheries at that time and accounted for nearly 60 percent of total fishery landings. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 229 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Salmon trollers at Bodega Bay.  River fishing for salmon in Calfornia wasdiscontinued in 1957, and the catch now comes solely from the ocean.  Thehigh price to the fishermen put salmon among the most valuable landings inCalifornia. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 230 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Picking Pacific oysters by hand at low tide.  The oysters are put into slattedtubs that have float lines attached. See image fish7990. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 250 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

The gear aboard this Hawaiian longliner is used to take bigeye and yellowfintunas and marlins and other billfishes from subsurface waters.  Baited hooksare suspended at intervals along the buoyed longline, which may be ten miles inlength.  Flags indicate the position of the longline in the water. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 286 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Hawaii's fisheries produce a colorful array of fish for the local fresh fishmarket. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 290 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

The fishpot is the most common gear in the Puerto Rico artisanal fisheries.Lined up on the beach are typical small boats, which take most of thecommercial catch.  Few truly large modern craft are operated by Puerto Ricans. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 298 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

A Samoan woman cracks a piece of coral to extract a hidden sea urchin.  Womenand youngsters comb the reefs around American Samoa for many kinds ofshellfish for use as food and to make shell leis and trinkets that will be soldto tourists.  Few Samoans engage in commercial fishing enterprises. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 312 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

Taiwanese fishermen unload albacore from a tuna longliner at an Americancannery in Pago Pago.  Fishery products, mainly canned tuna to be shipped to the United States, were valued at over $27 million in fiscal year 1967. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 318 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

At the annual fish day at Port Washington, youngsters participate in a smoked-fish eating contest. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 324 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Bringing bag of alewives aboard a commercial trawler .  Inforeground is powered drum used to haul in wings and main body of trawl net. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 329 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Pumping alewives from the hold of a Lake Michigan trawler.  This low-value fishwill be reduced to meal and oil.  Alewives migrated in from the Atlantic Oceanand have become the leading species in quantity taken from Great Lakes waters.Catches of high-value fish have declined seriously. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 330 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Commercial vessels, under contract to the BCF, skimming dead alewives from thesurface of Lake Michigan.  For years, dieoffs of overabundant alewives havecreated health and aesthetic problems. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 331 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Harvesting channel catfish that have been raised in an artificial pond. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 332 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Technician at the BCF Ann Arbor Biological Laboratory determines concentrationof pesticides in samples of river and lake water.  More study is needed toidentify toxic substances that may be dangerous or lethal to aquatic life andhumans when contaminated food is eaten. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 350 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Besides being a prime food fish, channel catfish raised artificially infishponds appeal to the sportsman. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 355 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Scuba diver 100 feet below surface studies abundance and behavior of thenorthern lobster, taken mainly in wooden pots along the New England coast. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 360 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

Bottom view of a hydraulic jet dredge developed to harvest surf clams and oceanquahogs previously unutilized.  The dredge is towed on the seafloor at depths of 30 to 100 feet, and clams are washed out of sand and gravel by high-pressurejets of water.  A v-shaped knife scoops up the clams; other jets are positionedto push the clams into the cage of the dredge for bringing to surface. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 368 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Northern shrimp taken during exploratory fishing in the Gulf of Maine.  Goodcatches have been made north of Cape Cod and a commercial fishery has beendeveloped.  About 13 million pounds were caught during the winter of 1967-1968. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 371 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Aerial spotting and photography are used to evaluate the magnitude and movements of pelagic untapped fishery resources. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 376 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Mullet taken in experimental gill net. Four species of mullet are abundant incoastal and estuarine waters throughout tropic, semitropic, and temperatezones.  These food fish - now caught in limited amounts - are a largely untapped resource in the West-Central Atlantic. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 381 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Behavior studies are conducted from underwater observation chamber on BCF shipCHARLES H. GILBERT.  Skipjack are characterized by horizontal stripes on thebelly.  When in a feeding frenzy, vertical bars appear and can be seen on thosefish near the surface where the bait has been cast. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 395 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

A research vessel is experimenting with an instrumented buoy system fortransmitting data to fishermen on the location, kinds, and abundance of fishschools.  Attached to the buoy are chemical receptors that detect chemicalresidues given off by the fish and detectors that register electromagneticchanges on sensing equipment. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 418 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

BCF scientists studying mating behavior of squid.  After mating, females deposit egg capsule strands on the calcareous sand bottom.  The lights have attractedthe squid to the locality.  In the background is Deep Diver, a researchsubmersible of Ocean Systems, Inc., from which the divers have emerged. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 437 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

Density and color enhancement of photograph of fish school and contrail byPhilco Ford for BCF.  To enhance readability of original photograph, whichconceals many details, each subtle tone is assigned a color.  This and otheradvanced techniques makes it possible to identify fish schools, changes in plant life in water, water depths, and polluted areas.  See images fish7971 and 7972. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 442 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Assembling computer at BCF Beaufort Biological Laboratory.  As fast asinformation can be collected, computers can store, analyze, print, contour, andmap for the fishery scientist. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 443 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Mass culture of algae under artificial light provides food for larval andjuvenile shellfish in BCF aquaculture programs.  Each 5-gallon glass containerproduces a continuous supply of suspended algae for about 4 months beforebecoming so contaminated that the culture must be replaced. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 448 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Selective breeding to improve growth of the eastern oyster is conducted at theBCF Milford Laboratory.  Oyster spat of differenct hybrids can be seen as smallround discs that have adhered to the scallop shells.  a technician willdetermine the growth rates of the various genetic crosses. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 452 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Laboratory scientist sorting larval shrimp that have been artificiallycultivated at the BCF Galveston Laboratory. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 453 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Fertilized salmon eggs are being placed on immersion incubator todetermine the best conditions for survival.  Through such research, bettermethods have been developed to cultivate the fish artificially through thecritical egg hatching and larval stages, and survival is improved. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 456 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Yellowfin tuna being thawed in water.  Excessive water pickup andsogginess can be a problem.  Increasing amounts of fish frozen at sea or frozenraw materials are being thawed for further processing.  Advanced electronic andvacuum-stema thawing techniques are being investigated. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 474 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

To bring fishery products of high quality to the consumer, tests are beingconsidered using helicopters to transport fish quickly to processing plants. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 477 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

Looking down at radiation cell at BCF Gloucester Technological Laboratory.Containers holding fish fillets are on a conveyor belt passing over the cell.The speed of the conveyor belt controls the radiation dose received by thefillets. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 482 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Three-mile fish ladder at Cazadero Dam.  Power dams have changed theenvironment drastically.  Ladders - some remarkably successful - are one meansof maintaining runs of salmon against effects of huge enginnering projects. Butnot all problems have been solved. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 492 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Injecting metal tag into a menhaden.  The tag will be recovered later, if thefish is recaptured and reduced to meal and oil.  This is part of an effort tomaintain the yield of menhaden and many other species.  Understanding ofvariations in abundance of fishery resources and of the effects of manmade andnatural phenomena is not complete. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 498 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Many fish cannot be harvested with present-day gear because the species arescattered over wide areas.  Experiments with pelagic fish show that it may bepossible to attract large numbers of fish at night to a series of buoys or rafts with pulsating lights.  Then the pulsations would move the fish to a suctionhose attached to a factory processing vessel. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 509 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

For many years, BCF oceanographers have worked with space technology to analyzedata from manned and unmanned spacecraft and have related these data toidentifying fertile areas in the ocean.  Satellite sensing could locate schoolsof fish and relay this information to fishing fleets.  Also, management andconservation of fishery resources could be improved. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 518 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

Shrimp vessels land the most valuable species taken along the South Atlanticcoast.  Shrimp trawlers have been modernized and are mainly double-rigged craftthat can tow two nets simultaneously, thereby increasing fishing efficiency.Here the trawler is washing its nets after a day of fishing. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 184 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

Mending a torn pound net.  Fishermen often spend much time repairing nets tornby debris or obstacles in the water or rough bottom. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 193 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Northern fur seal floating, asleep, with back flippers folded over on left front flipper. The fur seal fishery in the Bering Sea is an outstanding example ofsuccessful management.  The resource - after overexploitation caused a seriousdecline - has been restored by wise application of knowledge after many years of scientific research. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 497 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Bread made with 10 percent  concentrate from hake (center) and herring(right), hardly differ in texture and taste from regular bread (left).  FPC canbe added to many other products, like macaroni, cookies, vegetable proteins, and starchy foods.  About 1 ounce of FPC daily will provide a person with theminimum protein requirement. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 481 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

The shrimp-like euphausiid (upper) and the copepod occur in many kinds and often in great abundance.  These two groups of planktonic animals are of greatestimportance as food for larger animals, like fish, squid, or even whales.  In the Antarctic, euphausiids are the principal food of the blue whale. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 27 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Fertile areas of the ocean swarm with hundreds and hundreds of millions ofanimal plankton.  Some are visible as small dustlike particles; others can beseen only with a microscope.  The living zooplankton shown here contain twokinds of copepods - animals shaped like grains of rice - and one kind of arrowworm - the long slender animals at upper right and lower left. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 25 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

The diversity of tiny zooplankton is shown in this microphotograph of preservedspecimens.  The preserving fluid coagulates the protein and makes the animalslook white.  In nature the animals are nearly transparent.  Some zooplanktonlive by preying on their fellow members, but most are herbivorous, living onphytoplankton - the vegetation of the sea. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 24 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Samples of zooplankton taken at one time and place often consist of only a fewkinds of animals.  Several species of colorful copepods and one ostracod areshown here. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 27 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)
A salmon troller (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 117 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

491Estuaries and their marshlands are necessary as nursery grounds for some ofour most valuable fisherey resources.  Menhaden spawn in the open ocean , and as the larvae grow they move into estuarine waters where the juvenile stages feedand grow.  Yet, marshlands are being reclaimed at an alarming rate forindustrial and residential development. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 491 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Aerial photograph showing fish school with contrail.  The photograph was takenat an altitude of 3,000 feet. See image fish7948. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 441 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Aerial photograph showing fish school with contrail.  The photograph was takenat an altitude of 3,000 feet. See image fish7948. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 441 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Purse seines lead in quantity of fish landed by U.S. fishermen.  The purse line,when drawn to the vessel, effectively prevents the fish from escaping under thenet. Purse seines are used to catch schooling fish like tuna, menhaden, andsalmon.  Tuna purse seines (one is shown) are of enormous size, and may be 3/4mile long, 200 ft. deep, weight 15 tons, and have 10,000 floats. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 113 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

Scarlet prawns caught by BCF ship OREGON II during explorations for newshrimp grounds off northeastern South America.  This large deepwater speciesis widely distributed on the continental slope between 300 adn 1,000 fathoms inthe Gulf of Mexico and the Caribbean Sea.  These depths are well beyond thereach of present-day U.S. shrimp trawlers. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 386 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

A tracing made by an echo sounder shows concentrations of Pacific ocean perchon the sea floor, as well as the otter trawl of another vessel sweeping over the bottom toward the fish. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 420 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

The sea scallop - an inhabitant of waters off the Atlantic coast - is a striking example of genetic variation in nature.  Though the shape of the shell isuniform, markings and color in this single species vary widely.  Selectivebreeding for desirable traits (e.g., better flesh color or larger size) is oneof the goals of artificial cultivation. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 450 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

A converted ferryboat is used in the Potomac River by the Virginia Institute ofMarine Science to test the efficiency of a midwater trawl in catching alewivesas they migrate upstream to spawn. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 108 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Seining under ice for carp in a rough fish utilization operation.  Cropping anoverabundant fish often leads to better ecological balance and to improvedgrowth of the differenct species in a lake. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 415 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Bluefin tuna taken from subsurface waters with longline gear duringexploratory fishing by the BCF vessel DELAWARE.  Although explorationsshowed this species to be commercially abundant seasonally during the summerand fall in the Northwest Atlantic, an intensive commercial fishery has yet tobe developed. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 365 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Lobster pot floats hanging on wall of house.  In New England, nearlyevery port has a group of lobstermen each of whom has his own distinctivecolorful floats.  Pots belonging to each fisherman can easily be located whenthey are in the water. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 168 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Calico scallops, taken during exploratory fishing off Florida's east coast,spill out of dredge.  Successful explorations that locate untapped fisheryresources often lead to commercial harvesting. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 111 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

Blessing the shrimp fleet is an annual event.  Shrimp have become the mostvaluable species in the U.S. fisheries, and more than 2/3 of the domestic catchis taken from Gulf waters.  The shrimp fleet has been so improved  that it canbe considered one of the most modern seagoing fleets in the world. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 210 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

They that go down to the sea in ships.  Statue of Gloucester fishermancommemorating 300-year anniversary (1623-1923)  of fishing from this NewEngland port and also the thousands of men who have lost their lives in the NewEngland fisheries. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 170 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Scientists are able to determine the age of a fish by counting the number ofyearly deposits of bone on the otoliths  (ear bones) of fish.  Otoliths of thepollock  - a codlike fish - are being removed in a study of the growth of thespecies. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 97 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)
Aerial view of a purse seiner encircling a school of tuna. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 226 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Chemist at BCF College Park Laboratory injecting a sample of fatty acids into agas chromatograph.  Analysis yields information on the types and quantity offatty acids in a fish or shellfish. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 40 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Lobsterman preparing traps and floats before leaving port.  The northern lobster fishery - conducted principally in New England coastal waters - usuallyproduces more revenue for lobstermen than any other single species of NorthAtlantic fish or shellfish. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 182 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Swordfish caught below surface with longline gear.  Exploratory and commercialfishing in the Gulf of Mexico has shown that the fish concentrates in deep water in the fall, winter, and spring off the Mississippi Delta.  Profitable catchesare being made by U.S. vessels fishing at night. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 118 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Sacking 5-pound bags of scallops for freezing.  This new fishery - along withshrimp and crab fishing - is helping to diversify Alaska's fishing industry,which until recently depended almost entirely on the highly seasonal salmon andhalibut fisheries. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 278 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

When the tide is high, the tubs are lifted and emptied aboard vessel.  Dredgesand tongs are also used to harvest oysters.  See image fish7927. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 251 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Pumping alewives from a poundnet in Milwaukee Harbor.  This prolific fish- an invasive species in the Great Lakes - dominated Lake Michigan catchesduring the 1960's. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 412 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)
Captain of trawler at weighing platform. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 131 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Sashimi - raw tuna red in color and sliced thin - is part of this attractivearray of Japanese-style seafood and is popular across a multi-cultural spectrum. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 284 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Checking oyster raft at BCF Oxford Laboratory.  Shells or other hard objects areattached to suspended lines, and oyster spat in turn can attach to the hardobjects on which the spat grow to adult size. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 446 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Seining for small fish that will be used as live bait in the skipjack fishery.Nehu, an anchovy, is the most sought-after bait.  It is thrown into the water to attract skipjack close to the vessel where they can be caught with pole andline and unbaited barbless hooks. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 288 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Sockeye (red) salmon spawning in an Alaska stream.  The fish assume brilliantcolors as they migrate upriver to spawn. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 261 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume | Artwork by Bob Hines)

Fish wheel operated for river basin research on the Copper River.  Laws havebeen enacted to prevent commercial use of wheels, since almost every salmon isscooped up when the fish migrate toward spawning beds.  Wheels can still beoperated if the fish are caught for personal use. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 134 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Aquaculture has the potential to meet a large part of the demand for certainfishery products.  A technician at a privately owned facility is holding a bagof shells.  Free-swimming oyster larvae (spawned and grown artificially) attachto the shells and are then known as spat.  The spat are fed cultured algae until large enough to be placed on natural beds where they will grow until harvested. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection; P. 514 of Our Changing Fisheries 1970 Centenary NMFS centenary volume)

Salmon fishing with large loop nets by Indians at Celilo Falls, Oregon. A fine haul - At Astoria, Oregon, these men hauling in a beach seine heavy withColumbia River salmon. Alaska salmon roundup - Purse seining is an important method of taking salmon in the deep, swift waters of Alaska.  Salmon moving near the surface aresurrounded with a wall of netting, which is supported by corks or floats.  Lines are then drawn in the lower surface of the net to purse it into a baglikeshape.  The fish are then brailed out of the net. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection)

Goosefish (Lophiomus setigerus) also called angler, frogfish, and anko in Japan. They have a large grotesque head which constitutes the bulk of the fish.  Themouth is remarkably wide and having powerful jaw muscles and strong canine teeth.  Dermal flaps are scattered about over the head.  The first dorsal spine ismodified to form a lurelike device which is used to attract smaller fish.

58 bushels of green crabs (Carcinus maenus)  trapped in three days in town effort to reduce crab population.  These crabs were an invasive species andwere decimating local shell fisheries. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection)
Green crab (Carcinus maenus), an invasive species, pits on clam flats. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection)

The green crab (Carcinus maenus) reaches a maximum size of 3.5 inches inwidth.  Each crab can eat 15 small soft-shell clams per day.  The green crabis an invasive species, transported from northern Europe in the 1930's, (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection)

Green crabs, which have become abundant north of Cape Cod during recent warmwinter cycle are believed to be responsible for soft clam shortage. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection)

Dead green crabs after feeding upon chopped alewives treated with lindane, apesticide and sometimes pharmaceutical for treating scabies and lice. Thiswas a controlled experiment in Upper Landing Creek. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection)

Harry Davis, Fishery Research Biologist at the Milford Laboratory, changes water in cultures of clam larvae every other day and then adds food. The blue crab (Callinectes sapidus).  A female is shown at the top and a malebelow.  The female's claws are tipped with red and the male's with blue. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection | G. H. Rees BCF)

The range of the blue crab includes the entire Atlantic and Gulf coasts of theUnited States.  It is not very abundant north of Delaware Bay and thecommercial fishery extends from New Jersey to Texas.  As of 1965, over 75% ofthe total landings was caught in the 4 states shown in cross-hatching. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection)

The sex of the blue crab is easily recognizable by the shape of the abdomen.  It is triangular in the immature female (top), semi-circular in the adult female (center), and T-shaped in the male. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection | G. H. Rees BCF)

The male blue crab cradles his legs around the female and carries her aboutwith him for 2 or 3 days before and after mating.  At this time they are knownto watermen as doublers or buck and rider. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection | G. H. Rees BCF)

Sponge crab.  A female blue crab with a mass of eggs attached beneath herabdomen, where she carries them until they hatch.  The so-called sponge maycontain up to 2 million eggs. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection | G. B. Talbot BCF)

A zoea, the first larval form of the blue crab.  The zoea sheds 6 or 7 timesbefore entering the second larval form, known as a megalops. ( From Costlowand Bookhout) (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection)

A megalops, the second larval form of the blue crab.  The megalops sheds onceto become a miniature of its parents. (From Costlow and Bookhout.) (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection)

Molting.  the blue crab shown here has just begun to back out of its old shell.The new shell will stretch and smooth out as the crab absorbs water and willend up about 25 % larger than the former shell. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection | D. W. Windley BCF)

Artwork. Crab pot.  The crabs are attracted by the bait held in the cylindrical container and enter through the funnel-shaped openings, but find it hard toescape. Drawing by Curtis Lewis BCF. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection)

The fisherman dip nets the crabs as they are brought to thesurface.  (From Cargo.) (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection)

Artwork.  Crab dredge.  Pulled behind a boat, this device digs the crabs out ofthe mud, where they bury to escape the cold.  This is about the only way ofobtaining crabs in lower Chesapeake Bay during the winter. (Image credit: NOAA Central Library Historical Fisheries Collection)

desc: An early auxiliary powered halibut boat, the "Annie M. Nixon," built in 1894.
source: History of the Pacific Halibut Fishery by William F. Thomson and Norman L. Freeman (1930)

desc: The "Jennie F. Decker" in 1901, showing sails, dories amidships, and lack of cabin.
source: History of the Pacific Halibut Fishery by William F. Thomson and Norman L. Freeman (1930)

desc: An early steamer, the "Francis Cutting," on which some of the present captains were trained.
source: History of the Pacific Halibut Fishery by William F. Thomson and Norman L. Freeman (1930)

desc: The "Edith" In 1899
source: History of the Pacific Halibut Fishery by William F. Thomson and Norman L. Freeman (1930)

desc: Diagram of halibut gear as set.
source: History of the Pacific Halibut Fishery by William F. Thomson and Norman L. Freeman (1930)

desc: The "Roman," 1915. Her dories are "on the gear" and their place on the stern is vacant.
source: History of the Pacific Halibut Fishery by William F. Thomson and Norman L. Freeman (1930)

desc: A bucket of fish fron1 the hold. The latter is divided by bulwarks to prevent the shifting of crushed ice and fish. Photo by Ernest Pegler.
source: History of the Pacific Halibut Fishery by William F. Thomson and Norman L. Freeman (1930)

desc: A deck load of halibut in the early days. Photograph by Webster and Stevens.
source: History of the Pacific Halibut Fishery by William F. Thomson and Norman L. Freeman (1930)

desc: Putting the dories overboard fron1 a steamer at half-speed.
source: History of the Pacific Halibut Fishery by William F. Thomson and Norman L. Freeman (1930)

desc: A dory at "vork. The line is taken in over the gurdy, the fish thrown in the landing net, and the gear coiled in front of the standing fisherman.
source: History of the Pacific Halibut Fishery by William F. Thomson and Norman L. Freeman (1930)

desc: Halibut vessel of older type, showing anchor cable. In foreground one of early chutes for setting gear. Seattle, 1915. Contrast with "Marmot" and "Pioneer."
source: History of the Pacific Halibut Fishery by William F. Thomson and Norman L. Freeman (1930)

desc: One of the first attempts at long-lining or fishing directly from the deck. On the "James Carruthers," off Yakutat, 1913. Note the ice on the deck and the fishermen helping the line overboard.
source: History of the Pacific Halibut Fishery by William F. Thomson and Norman L. Freeman (1930)

desc: The powered gurdy which pulls the line in over the roller, while the fishern1an coils. Photograph by Ernest Pegler.
source: History of the Pacific Halibut Fishery by William F. Thomson and Norman L. Freeman (1930)

desc: An unwanted gray cod comes over the roller and is jerked off. Photograph by Ernest Pegler.
source: History of the Pacific Halibut Fishery by William F. Thomson and Norman L. Freeman (1930)

desc: A Diesel-powered dory vessel of a type still in use. Built in 1914. The dories are nested on the stern, there is a gurdy amidships, and a steel anchor cable and winch forward.
source: History of the Pacific Halibut Fishery by William F. Thomson and Norman L. Freeman (1930)

desc: The "Marmot," built in 1926. A modern Diesel-powered long-line boat. Her dories are not for fishing. Note the electric lights, power gurdy, canvas shelter for bait tables, and chute on the stern. The sail is almost lacking.
source: History of the Pacific Halibut Fishery by William F. Thomson and Norman L. Freeman (1930)
